I often wonder if millennials might be the last generation capable of appreciating art purely and establishing connections with artists, without the pressure to view everything through critical lenses.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but this collective consciousness has since vanished.
Back then, we could immerse ourselves directly in the content without considering its source, as tracing origins was not easy in those days.
We worship these artists like gods, and there is no reason to question this adoration. Consequently, we have established a "symbiotic social relationship" with them, regarding it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so enchanted by nostalgia.
While "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch the episodes together while munching on pizza.
This contrasts sharply with our current experience of watching shows via streaming platforms, which typically release 12 episodes at once, allowing everyone to watch at their own pace, with spoiler warnings posted on social media when discussing plot twists, or simply keeping discussions within specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all yearn for the sense of collective belonging that connected us all.
It is precisely this sense of nostalgia that compels us to rewatch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Broadcast News," reliving those unforgettable lines from the scripts, which spread widely online like memes.
We quote these classic lines from the works and assume that most people will understand them.
Now, we can't take it for granted that everyone has seen something just because it went viral online.
Now with information explosion, there's so much we need to pay attention to that it's impossible to simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape from this state of information overload?
We discover new media and new artists over and over again, only to find they are either notorious sexual predators or bigoted holdouts, repeating this cycle endlessly, growing tiresome.
We are caught between our nostalgia and the undeniable reality that the creators of the art we adore might have severe moral flaws, leaving us at a loss.
We will be even more careful in establishing a "symbiotic social relationship" with artists.
We gradually realized that if one wants to acquire wealth and power, it is difficult to avoid hurting or exploiting others.
Because the collective consciousness of media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who stubbornly idolize others, only to appear shocked when their idols fall.
We are living in a time of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
Inclusivity and safety should be the defaults.
